Environmental, Social, and Governance (ESG) has garnered increasing attention in recent years, prompting many institutional investors to exclusively support companies that furnish ESG performance reports. ESG encompasses factors that are pertinent to analysts, investors, consumers, and employees, making it a prominent topic of discussion in boardrooms. This course provides a comprehensive overview of the ESG framework and its role in bolstering a company's overall risk management. It delves into each constituent aspect, offering insights into how they collectively influence a company and its stakeholders. The course also explores the examination of corporate pressures and stakeholder expectations, elucidating their impact on risk identification and business success. Lastly, critical considerations from both the company and investor perspectives are explored.


By completing this course, participants will gain the ability to:


Explain what ESG is and its relevance to making financial decisions;
Describe key environmental, social, and governance issues;
Explain how stakeholders influence corporate ESG performance;
Analyze ESG risks and opportunities;
Assess ESG company performance using publicly available information;
Translate ESG information to business intelligence.
This ESG course is ideal for analysts seeking a deeper understanding of how companies navigate risks and seize opportunities arising from dynamic market and non-market conditions in the contemporary business environment.
